Physicochemical Properties of Protein Tertiary Structure¶

For this project, we will be using a Linear Generalized Additive Model and the Nadaraya-Watson kernel density estimator to analyze Protein Structure data. To calculate the quality of our predictions, we'll look at the R^2 coefficient as well as RSME with 10 cross-fold validations.

Using the Yellowbrick library, we'll show a residual scatterplot and histogram for one of our K-Folds. This graph will help show any patterns of error in our models.

Definitions¶

Class GAMsk is created for later use of Yellowbrick to analyze and graph residuals.

Function run_Kfold is created to run a K-Fold cross validation loop for later use. This function uses Yellowbrick to print a residual scatterplot and histogram of a k-fold.

This function also calculates the Root Mean Square Error of the model on each Train/Test set. The function returns the average Train and Test error of the model across all k-folds.

In [ ]:
class GAMsk(BaseEstimator, RegressorMixin):
    def __init__(self, ns= None):
        self.ns = ns
        
    def fit(self, X, y,):
        X, y = check_X_y(X, y)

        if self.ns is None:
            gam = LinearGAM(n_splines= 12).gridsearch(X, y, keep_best = True,objective='GCV')
            self.pred_ = gam
        else:
            gam = LinearGAM(n_splines=self.ns).gridsearch(X, y, keep_best = True, objective='GCV')
            self.pred_ = gam
        return self
    
    def predict(self, X):
        check_is_fitted(self)
        X = check_array(X)
        return self.pred_.predict(X).reshape(-1,1)
In [ ]:
def run_Kfold(X, y, k, random, modelTest):
  count = 0
  PredErrorInternal = []
  PredErrorExternal = []
  kf = KFold(n_splits = k, shuffle = True, random_state = random)
  for idxtrain, idxtest in kf.split(X):
    X_train = X[idxtrain,:]
    y_train = y[idxtrain]
    X_test = X[idxtest,:]
    y_test = y[idxtest]
    model = modelTest
    model = model.fit(X_train, y_train.ravel())
    yhat_test = model.predict(X_test)
    yhat_train = model.predict(X_train)
    PredErrorExternal.append(mse(y_test, yhat_test, squared = False))
    PredErrorInternal.append(mse(y_train, yhat_train, squared = False))
    ##For our final K-fold, we'll create a scatter plot and histogram of our residuals
    if count == (k):
      visualizer = ResidualsPlot(model)
      visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)
      visualizer.score(X_test, y_test)
      visualizer.poof()  

    count = count + 1
    
  return np.mean(PredErrorExternal), np.mean(PredErrorInternal)

Linear GAM¶

The linear GAM model is created with 12 splines, which showed best results in early testing stages of this project.

In [ ]:
model = GAMsk(ns= 12)

Graphing our Linear GAM Residuals¶

After performing a Linear GAM analysis using 10-fold cross validation, the Linear GAM model had a RMSE external error 4.976465884428406 of and a RMSE internal error of 4.961546125536189.

The R^2 of the model was .339 on the Train data and .371 on the Test data. This low R^2 suggests that either Linear GAM is poorly suited to this dataset, or that the model was poorly optimized.

The residual scatterplot exhibits characteristics of a bad model. The residuals are not evenly distributed and appear to have clear trends in both the Training and Test sets.

The residual Histogram shows that the residuals are not entirely normally distributed, and are not symettrical at 0.

The residuals appear heteroscedastic and indicate that the LinearGAM model has consistent error and is not working well for this data set.

Nadaraya-Watson Kernel Density Estimator¶

Because the Nadaraya-Watson implementation automatically uses k-fold validation, I didn't create a k-fold loop like I used for the LinearGAM implmentation. Instead, just uses a simple Train/Test split to show a train/test residual histogram. The model's R^2 and RMSE were still calculated using 10-fold cross validation that is encapsulated within the model.

The Nadaraya-Watson Kernel Density Estimator had an overall Test RMSE of 4.037633142782846 and a mean R^2 = .5510379747700558 over the test datasets. These results are fairly poor, but still indicate better performance than the LinearGAM model.

The residual plots shows some of the same trends present in the LinearGAM model, but with a more normalized residual histogram that is more symmetrical across 0.

Summary¶

Linear GAM did a poor job of predicting Protein Folding based on the input data. The residuals showed heteroscedasticity that indicates the Linear GAM model was not suitable for the dataset.

The Nadaraya-Watson model had improved prediction accuracy but still had some worrying trends in the residual plot.

Both models had similarly shaped irregular residual plots, which could indicate that there is a variable we are not accounting for, or that the models were poorly fit to the data. Both models have similar "bounded" looking distributions.
